04549nam a22005655i 9780822386759DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223867597 a10.1515/97808223867592doi  a(DE-B1597)553423  a(OCoLC)1226680285  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHD6200b.P86 2005 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a331.4/87/09511 aNgai, Pun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMade in China :bWomen Factory Workers in a Global Workplace /cPun Ngai. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b6 photos, 5 tables, 2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 State Meets Capital: The Making and Unmaking of a New Chinese Working Class -- t2 Marching from the Village: Women's Struggles between Work and Family -- t3 The Social Body, the Art of Discipline and Resistance -- t4 Becoming Dagongmei: Politics of Identities and Di√erences -- t5 Imagining Sex and Gender in the Workplace -- t6 Scream, Dream, and Transgression in the Workplace -- t7 Approaching a Minor Genre of Resistance -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs China has evolved into an industrial powerhouse over the past two decades, a new class of workers has developed: the dagongmei, or working girls. The dagongmei are women in their late teens and early twenties who move from rural areas to urban centers to work in factories. Because of state laws dictating that those born in the countryside cannot permanently leave their villages, and familial pressure for young women to marry by their late twenties, the dagongmei are transient labor. They undertake physically exhausting work in urban factories for an average of four or five years before returning home. The young women are not coerced to work in the factories; they know about the twelve-hour shifts and the hardships of industrial labor. Yet they are still eager to leave home. Made in China is a compelling look at the lives of these women, workers caught between the competing demands of global capitalism, the socialist state, and the patriarchal family.Pun Ngai conducted ethnographic work at an electronics factory in southern China's Guangdong province, in the Shenzhen special economic zone where foreign-owned factories are proliferating. For eight months she slept in the employee dormitories and worked on the shop floor alongside the women whose lives she chronicles. Pun illuminates the workers' perspectives and experiences, describing the lure of consumer desire and especially the minutiae of factory life. She looks at acts of resistance and transgression in the workplace, positing that the chronic pains-such as backaches and headaches-that many of the women experience are as indicative of resistance to oppressive working conditions as they are of defeat. Pun suggests that a silent social revolution is underway in China and that these young migrant workers are its agents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFactory systemzChina. 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspectszChina. 0aWomenxEmploymentzChina. 0aWomenzChinaxEconomic conditions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822386759zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386759423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822386759.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles